   "source": [
    "### Merging of several StationData objects into one \n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook illustrates to can merge several instances StationData objects into one objects. This merging only works for data from the same station and a typical case is if the data source files for one station are separated into many single files containing only parts of the data (e.g. if the files contain only one year of data). \n",
    "\n",
    "In the following, the example of the EBAS database is used for illustration. In particular, we will focus on the retrieval of the aerosol light scattering coefficients at 550 nm (**scatc550aer** in AEROCOM naming convention) for the station ***Jungfraujoch***, located in Germany."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Initating pyaerocom configuration\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Checking database access...\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Checking access to: /lustre/storeA\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Access to lustre database: True\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Init data paths for lustre\n"
     ]

   "source": [

    "\n",
    "Let's have a look at the respective time-series for both stations. First, convert into instance of `StationData` class and then plot."

    "#### Comment for convenience....\n",
    "\n",
    "Actually, in the default setup you do not really need to think about all this. As you might have recognised, when creating the list of `StationData` objects from the `UngriddedData` object (using method `to_station_data`) we parsed the argument `merge_if_multi=False`.\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "source": [
    "What's happening here is, that `to_station_data` internally creates a list of `StationData` objects and uses the above illustrated method `merge_station_data` at the end if the input argument `merge_if_multi=True`. "

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### What about overlapping data ??\n",
    "\n",
    "In some situations, there may be overlapping conflicts when merging multiple time series into one long time-series. In the following, we illustrate how these overlaps are handled if they occur. \n",
    "\n",
    "The method `merge_station_data` that is illustrated above has some features to handle overlapping data and in any case, all overlaps that were detected are stored in the `overlap` attribute of the merged `StationData` object. Let's check first if there are any overlaps in the Jungfraujoch data:"

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### How to prioritise certain stations from others, when deciding what goes into overlap and what into the final timeseries?\n",
    "\n",
    "The method `merge_station_data` provides a bunch of options to handle that. Things do not be written twice so please read the docstring of the method:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Help on function merge_station_data in module pyaerocom.helpers:\n",
      "\n",
      "merge_station_data(stats, var_name, pref_attr=None, sort_by_largest=True, fill_missing_nan=True, **add_meta_keys)\n",
      "    Merge multiple StationData objects (from one station) into one instance\n",
      "    \n",
      "    Note\n",
      "    ----\n",
      "    - all input :class:`StationData` objects need to have same attributes       ``station_name``, ``latitude``, ``longitude`` and ``altitude``\n",
      "    \n",
      "    Parameters\n",
      "    ----------\n",
      "    stats : list\n",
      "        list containing :class:`StationData` objects (note: all of these \n",
      "        objects must contain variable data for the specified input variable)\n",
      "    var_name : str\n",
      "        data variable name that is to be merged\n",
      "    pref_attr \n",
      "        optional argument that may be used to specify a metadata attribute\n",
      "        that is available in all input :class:`StationData` objects and that\n",
      "        is used to order the input stations by relevance. The associated values\n",
      "        of this attribute need to be sortable (e.g. revision_date). This is \n",
      "        only relevant in case overlaps occur. If unspecified the relevance of \n",
      "        the stations is sorted based on the length of the associated data \n",
      "        arrays.\n",
      "    sort_by_largest : bool\n",
      "        if True, the result from the sorting is inverted. E.g. if \n",
      "        ``pref_attr`` is unspecified, then the stations will be sorted based on\n",
      "        the length of the data vectors, starting with the shortest, ending with\n",
      "        the longest. This sorting result will then be inverted, if \n",
      "        ``sort_by_largest=True``, so that the longest time series get's highest\n",
      "        importance. If, e.g. ``pref_attr='revision_date'``, then the stations \n",
      "        are sorted by the associated revision date value, starting with the \n",
      "        earliest, ending with the latest (which will also be inverted if \n",
      "        this argument is set to True)\n",
      "    fill_missing_nan : bool\n",
      "        if True, the resulting time series is filled with NaNs. NOTE: this \n",
      "        requires that information about the temporal resolution (ts_type) of\n",
      "        the data is available in each of the StationData objects.\n",
      "\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "help(pya.helpers.merge_station_data)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In particular, `pref_attr` and `sort_by_largest` are relevant here. \n",
    "\n",
    "**NOTE**: if `pref_attr` is unspecified, then the stations are sorted based on the number of valid measurement points for the input variable. This was done in the merged time series that we retrieved above.\n",
    "\n",
    "Now, in the following, let's not use the number of available data points (to sort the stations by relevance) but prefer stations that have a more recent data revision date."
   ]

   "cell_type": "code",

    "except pya.exceptions.MetaDataError as e:\n",
    "    print('Failed merging, error: {}'.format(repr(e)))"
   ]
